comments.body:
The enrichment fields in alma specifies 876 | h as: call_number subfield. This is why based on the current codebase it indexes the call number. This should be fixed.

In voyager an 876 | h would expect to have 'In library use', 'Supervised Use' or nothing. The logic is based on the item location. https://github.com/pulibrary/marc_liberation/blob/alma/app/adapters/alma_adapter/alma_item.rb

Update: We discussed this in the alma checkin and we removed from all the publishing jobs the `876 | h` and `876 | i` subfields.
 Publishing jobs that it was removed: General Publishing via FTP, Incremental Publishing via FTP, Sample Record FTP export, Test record export
I will update these fixtures tomorrow. https://github.com/pulibrary/marc_liberation/pull/1116

pulfalight.title: Requests for "/collections/eadid/componentid" should redirect to "/catalog/eadid_componentid"

comments.body: For clarification, an `eadid` here refers to the finding aid identifier. In cases such as https://findingaids-beta.princeton.edu/catalog/C0101_c013317, `C0101` is the finding aid identifier/EAD ID. These are migrated from the legacy platform, using the legacy URL structure: https://findingaids.princeton.edu/collections/C0101.

Component IDs are individual levels of nested archival material items within a collection description. Component IDs are "levels" of archival collection description. For example:

- Archives of Charles Scribner's Sons, 1786-2004, bulk 1880/1979
  - Series 1: Advertising Records, 1917-1964 (large gaps), 1917-1964
    - Subseries 1A: Advertising Records, 1917-1950
    
...where each component leads to a more nested level of description. As each collection description is a tree node, the leaf node for each is typically a level of description which indicates that a physical box or folder is being described.
